## Semantic Color Tokens

The theme defines semantic color tokens in `src/app/globals.css` that automatically adapt to light/dark mode. Always prefer these over hardcoded Tailwind colors.

### Available tokens

| Token | Purpose | Light | Dark |
|-------|---------|-------|------|
| `destructive` | Errors, deletions, price increases | Red | Red |
| `success` | Confirmations, positive states, price drops | Emerald | Emerald |
| `info` | Informational notices, links, neutral highlights | Blue (primary-600) | Blue (primary-700) |
| `warning` | Caution banners, allergens, degraded states | Amber | Amber |
| `primary` / `secondary` | Brand colors | Theme-defined | Theme-defined |

Each token also has a `-foreground` variant for text on solid backgrounds (e.g. `text-info-foreground` on `bg-info`).

### Usage patterns

**Solid backgrounds** (badges, buttons):
```
bg-success text-white
bg-warning text-warning-foreground
bg-info text-info-foreground
```

**Subtle/glass backgrounds** (banners, callouts, cards):
```
bg-info/10 border-info/20 text-info
bg-warning/10 border-warning/20 text-warning
bg-destructive/10 border-destructive/20 text-destructive
```

Dark mode is handled automatically by the CSS variable swap — no `dark:` prefix needed for semantic tokens.

### Callout component

Use `<Callout>` from `@/components/ui/callout` for info/warning/error banner patterns:

```tsx
<Callout variant="info" icon={InfoIcon}>Message here</Callout>
<Callout variant="warning">Warning message</Callout>
```

### When hardcoded colors are acceptable

- Brand logos and store-specific colors (e.g. Continente red, Auchan green)
- Chart/data visualization colors (use `--chart-*` tokens when possible)
- One-off decorative elements that don't carry semantic meaning

### What to avoid

- `bg-blue-*`, `text-blue-*` for info states → use `bg-info`, `text-info`
- `bg-amber-*`, `text-amber-*` for warnings → use `bg-warning`, `text-warning`
- `bg-emerald-*`, `bg-green-*` for success → use `bg-success`, `text-success`
- `bg-red-*` for errors → use `bg-destructive`, `text-destructive`
- Explicit `dark:` overrides for semantic colors → the token handles it
